(193, 1, '2020-01-15 13:08:11', '2020-01-15 13:08:11', '', '2019-12-03', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'closed', '', '2019-12-03-2', '', '', '2020-01-15 13:08:11', '2020-01-15 13:08:11', '', 145, 'http://www.efrog.com.au/blog/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/2019-12-03.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
(195, 1, '2020-01-15 13:08:37', '2020-01-15 13:08:37', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Localized Websites are able to communicate effortlessly with a brand’s targeted customer. A localized website is a specialist in conveying a special kind of information that cannot be achieved with mere machine translation. Unlike a generic stock brand webpage, the localized website is especially suited for meeting a customer’s needs, be it cultural, currency-based, language-based or the desire for products or services with a personal touch.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To help your brand website emote and communicate like a native and appear inviting and pleasant to a local populace, we have uncovered the following 5 secrets to successfully localized websites:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2> Identifying a Target Market </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":149} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://www.efrog.com.au/blog/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/1.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-149\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The first logical step is deciding in which country to market a brand’s products and services. The following questions help to shape this decision:&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Is the country interested in the product?</li><li>Will the targeted consumer willingly choose the brand?</li><li>Can the business survive the already existing competition?</li><li>Is the brand’s product or service affordable to the targeted consumer?</li><li>Does that country’s market promise a healthy growth rate?</li><li>Are product delivery costs in the country manageable?</li><li>Is Customer Support in the local tongue affordable for the business?</li><li>Will the ROI justify the investment in website localization?</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The sensible thing to do is to first enter a market where there is the highest probability of the product getting sold. As costs can increase with multiple target countries and languages, it is better to start small and go with the flow until the brand finds new emerging markets.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If the brand’s product is a bestseller in one particular region, it should be treated like a benchmark around which the rest of the business plan can be figured out.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The objective is to reach the highest number of potential customers without crossing the budget. After the marketing and financial indicators mentioned above have been studied, a business should consider the experiences of others regarding specific markets and learn from that as well. For example - the stories of Nike and Mercedes-Benz in China clearly prove that the cultural appropriateness of a product and its marketing technique are MORE IMPORTANT than plain statistics. China has a MASSIVE customer base (a misleading statistic from a business perspective) that is mostly untapped. This is because the localized websites operating here till date had been initially forced to explore the market without rock-solid guidance or expertise in Chinese culture and linguistics. Let\'s see what happened.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Nike</strong>: They designed white sneakers for The Year of the Monkey. The Chinese character on the left shoe, Fa (發), supposedly means good fortune. The character on the right shoe, Fu (福), is believed to denote wealth. Nike understandably thought that they have invented an excellent marketing gimmick. Despite their sincere efforts, this gimmick bombed. What they failed to grasp is that Chinese characters change in meaning when used in combination. So when the wearer of the sneakers joined heels, the resulting message, instead of “good fortune and wealth,” read “fat!”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Mercedes-Benz</strong>: This company chose the phonetically-similar name “Ben-Si” (奔死), instead of “Benz,” to penetrate the Chinese market. But when they unwittingly implemented this decision, the two characters “Ben” and “Si,” when combined, advertized to Chinese consumers a brand name “run to death!”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Moral</strong>: Every market or country has its own quirks and unique qualities that have to be looked into so that disasters like the ones mentioned here can be avoided.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Build your Business from Scratch Around a Localized Website</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As of <a href=\"https://www.statista.com/statistics/617136/digital-population-worldwide/\">October 2019</a>, 58% of earth’s population is now online. That amounts to a staggering 4.48 billion users worldwide; with China, India and the United States leading the way. While this huge number may not be an established consumer base for a particular brand, it certainly is a market filled with potential that shouldn\'t be left unutilized. So obviously if a business ignores this global market and instead confines itself to a single country or continent, it is missing out. Which is why in this day and age, building (and growing) a business and localizing the business website for a number of regions go hand-in-hand.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Another interesting business insight is that consumer behaviour across the globe is now following similar trends, if not&nbsp; the same trend. Unlike earlier, if a product is successful in one particular geography there isn’t any reason why it shouldn’t do well in another. <strong>Important</strong>: While the demand for a particular product can be felt in the same strong way the world over, no one has said that it needs to be marketed in the same way everywhere.&nbsp; Hence the need to communicate in the local language. Hence the need for localized websites!<br><strong>Let’s drop yet another significant fact</strong>: English remains to be the most widespread and most used language, but other languages, particularly Chinese, are catching up. 72.4% of global shoppers prefer to use their native language when shopping online. 55% of global shoppers only buy products from websites that give information in their native language. 56.2% of the world’s consumers find the ability to obtain information in their own language to be more important than price. These <a href=\"http://www.oneskyapp.com/blog/14-compelling-statistics-about-the-importance-of-localization/\">facts and figures</a> clearly show the need for a localized website. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Keeping Design Flexible</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":150} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://www.efrog.com.au/blog/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/2.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-150\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The average word length of the English language is 4.7 characters. Languages like German and Mongolian have average word lengths between 11.5 and 12. The distribution of <a href=\"http://www.ravi.io/language-word-lengths\">word lengths</a> in various languages is vastly varied.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When we apply this fact to a practical context, like trying to squeeze the German text “in den Warenkorb legen” on a button that originally read “Add to Cart” in English, we can appreciate the importance of this fact.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Arabic text has a right-to-left reading direction. Chinese, Japanese and Korean texts are written and read vertically.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Therefore, keeping all these variances in mind, it makes sense to keep the website design flexible and leave at least 20% extra space within menus and buttons. A cluttered layout and hard-coded CTA URLs lead to broken design, string collapse, haphazard navigation and slow speed.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So giving a website plenty of breathing space is the best way to insure it against different internet speeds in different regions. Keeping a website light by minimizing the amount of visual imagery helps it run faster. Also, keeping the quantity of images under control makes tailoring and localizing it a lot less time-consuming.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2> “Internationalizing” a Website by using Unicode</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A total of 110–116 different characters exist across the different languages of the world. It is a happy thought that a website doesn\'t necessarily need to display each and every one of them. But a point to consider is that some or many of them may end up as strange symbols instead of being displayed correctly.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Unicode is used to counter this problem. The UTF-8 encoding format is reliable for handling most compatibility issues. UTF-16 is better suited for Chinese, Japanese and Devanagari.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Developers divide source codes and separate translatable strings so that translators can help them to adapt all the existing website data to the new language. Content is separated from the code and stored so that future website localization operations don’t require a repeat of breaking strings. Local preferences like the formats of mail addresses, data and time, numbers, calendars, currency, shipping address, etc have to have codes enabled. This functionality helps users make decisions on buying products and services without having to work out the math. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Local Keyword Research</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":151} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://www.efrog.com.au/blog/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/3.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-151\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Google Search doesn’t enjoy a presence in each and every nation on earth. Freshly localized websites need to feature in the results page of native search engines. Baidu is the most popular search engine in China. Yandex is the most popular search engine in Russia.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The keywords that are required to do this cannot be merely translated. A&nbsp; local SEO specialist is required to identify the right terms that the translator can include on the website immediately. Backlink creation is also something that needs to be done from scratch. A list of keywords needs to be drawn up.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Translators then check the list for on-page and off-page applicability. They check metadata, the keyword density on the website and external link anchors.<br><strong>Important</strong>: a localized website isn’t just for markets differentiated by language. It has been observed that some nations that speak the same language like the UK and the USA, Mexico and Argentina, etc don\'t speak the common language in the same way. To make sure that a business website has a good position on the SERP, some solid keyword research is required to make sure that everyone involved in the business fully understands the differences in vocabulary between <a href=\"https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/six-difference-between-britsh-and-american-english/3063743.html\">two countries divided by a common language</a>. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Apart from Language Translation...</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> In addition to linguistic translation efforts; images, messages, and even colors have to be localised for a target audience. For example, Australia doesn’t play in the snow in December. Also, any user, anywhere any the world, unconsciously responds better to imagery that contains the same ethnicity as the target market. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Attention to Local Law and Regulations</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> Every nation has different laws and regulations concerning terms of service, privacy, data protection, etc. For example, GDPR does not apply as harshly or strictly elsewhere in the world as it does within the EU, unless specifically mandated by the European Parliament or Union or by a country like Australia that has an overlap of the GDPR with its own Privacy Principles. To wade through these legal waters, the services of a local legal specialist is NOT an extravagance. Rather, one should think about how the cost is a lot LESS than any legal fee incurred on violating local law. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2> Localized Social Media Strategy</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Some quick facts</strong>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Norway and Australia are the only two countries where <a href=\"https://www.emarketer.com/content/global-social-network-users-2019\">Snapchat</a> is more popular than Instagram.&nbsp;</li><li>India has 270 million Facebook users. Next comes the US, with 190. Third place is taken by Indonesia with 130 million. Facebook is banned in Bangladesh, China, Iran and North Korea.&nbsp;</li><li>Twitter is banned in China, Iran and North Korea. The US is the top twitter base at 47 million users. Japan comes next at 38.6 million. The UK comes third with 13.6 million.&nbsp;</li><li>China leads in LinkedIn use with 40.6 million users. Brazil is next with 32.6 million. The UK is third at 22.7 million. LinkedIn is blocked in Russia.</li><li>China, Iran and Korea have blocked Instagram completely. The US has the biggest number of Instagram users, 110 million. Brazil is at second place with 57 million and Indonesia comes next at 53 million.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Clearly, the right platform has to be used when building reach and engaging consumers. The localised website should display the right social sharing buttons.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Excellent Bonding and Cohesion in the Team</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Localization is hard is because there are a lot of people involved.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A successful business needs people on board who understand what makes the market tick. This includes translators, preferably native. They should be good at transcreation. Developers should be able to work well and collaborate with translators. The nature of the undertaking of localizing a website is such that the team is likely to be distributed across different time zones and geographies.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Localized Customer Support</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Customers appreciate support in their native language. A business should provide its consumers with local phone numbers and addresses if it can. It makes the business appear more reliable, trustworthy and approachable to its customers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Customer Support should be trained and prepared to handle inquiries in local languages. In case hiring native speaking staff exceeds the budget, templates in all languages that answer common questions should be made visible and available.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Convenient Payment Options</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":152} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://www.efrog.com.au/blog/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/4.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-152\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is a critical parameter. Getting a bunch of new customers to the checkout page takes quite some work. Losing them at this point is VERY disappointing. If a willing consumer doesn’t find preferred payment options, It’ll take nothing for him to just&nbsp; click out of his browser and just forget about the whole thing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To make sure that isn\'t the case ever, here’s a handy list of <a href=\"https://addons.prestashop.com/en/content/35-the-most-popular-online-payment-methods-by-country\">payment options by country</a>. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Translation Management Software</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Manually localizing a website is legitimately one of the worst things a human being can do to himself. Spreadsheets and emails have a margin of error that is just too high.&nbsp;<br>The right translation management tool allows translators to type directly onto the website. Use this convenient <a href=\"http://capterra.com/translation-management-software/\">list</a> to find a software package that can let your project management, developers and translators localize your brand website with ease. It is better to invest in a software than to try to save money in this area and end up in spreadsheet and word hell.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Testing Before Launch</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Particular areas to pay attention to are how fast or how slow the website is loading at the user’s end so that the first impression on a new audience is not abysmal.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Testing and improvement should continue after the website is up and running. The business should necessarily request for feedback through surveys. This will increase the conversion rate.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Linguistic testing should check that every word appearing on the website is correctly translated, accurate and 100% understood by the intended audience.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Localization testing should check encryption algorithms, hardware compatibility, units of measurement, names, date, time, entry fields, links, etc.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>All images should be appropriate.</li><li>The website should load correctly on all kinds of mobile devices and browsers.</li><li>Images shouldn’t take time to load and videos shouldn’t buffer or struggle to start.</li><li>Programmers must be made to streamline the HTML, remove unnecessary CSS and optimize the JavaScript.&nbsp;</li><li>A Content Delivery Network, or CDN helps by using local servers to speed up the loading of a website.</li><li>QA should be split out over regions and made to go through all site forms to check their function and look for broken design.</li><li>If the website is burdened with too much image and video, site speed will be slower than what a user might be willing to tolerate. It is better to shave off imagery and visualisations that you think are important than have 40% of potential consumers leave the website after waiting for more than three seconds for it to load.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Just Keep Calm and Do Your Best</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Website localization certainly seems daunting.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But our curation of best practices should get you through it. If you feel frustrated or overwhelmed; or you are just too busy with far more critical aspects of your life and business, the expertise of eFrog will make everything EASY. You have the option to tap into our incredible resources and capabilities of digitizing a business. We have a <a href=\"http://www.efrog.com.au/blog/\">rich repository of helpful articles</a> to help with any aspect of your business. Learn how to make the most of your budget and still do a hell of a job in marketing your business online by clicking <a href=\"http://www.efrog.com.au/blog/2019/09/10/how-to-promote-your-business-online/\">here</a>. Alternatively, you can have our undivided attention in a free consultation by simply clicking <a href=\"http://www.efrog.com.au/#contactForm\">here</a>.&nbsp;<br>So stop hesitating. Take your first step towards a successfully localized website today!\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Top 5 Secrets to Successfully Localized Websites - Uncovered!', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '145-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-01-15 13:08:37', '2020-01-15 13:08:37', '', 145, 'http://www.efrog.com.au/blog/145-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
