(204, 1, '2020-01-15 13:20:11', '2020-01-15 13:20:11', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>“A product can be quickly outdated, but a successful brand is timeless.”</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What makes a successful business? The fastest answer would be – the product or service you offer!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Well, not quite right…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While the product or service is a crucial key for a business to run, but there is something more to it. You can be the best consultant or service provider the world ever saw and no one would come knocking at your door. The answer to that problem is branding! The way people perceive your business can often be more important than the things you offer! Despite that, not a lot of people see that. In this article, I will tell you the most common misconceptions about branding you need to know.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>We don’t need to be special, Let’s fit everyone:</strong></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Every business needs a USP to stand out. If your business doesn’t have any USP, how you going to decide the tone and things while marketing your business. Let me make it more simple for you, When we see a logo of Mcdonald’s the very first thing comes in our mind is “Burgers”. You know why? Because that’s their USP, that makes them stand out from other fast-food chains. So, before marketing your business, you need to figure out what’s your or your business’s USP.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Branding is just a name and logo:</strong></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Logo, the name of your business is a part of your branding, but branding is much more than a name or a logo.&nbsp;Branding is all about the feelings, features, and emotions associated with your company. Let’s take the example&nbsp;of the “Liverpool Football Club”. We all are very well aware of LFC, the fans of LFC have an emotional attachment with it, that’s made the Liverpool Football club so popular among all the football fan across the world.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Customers only care about product / service:</strong></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Actually, customers care a lot about choosing a brand that appeals to them and are able to connect with. A&nbsp;stuntman or a fan of extreme sports are more likely to pick a Red Bull energy drink over, for example, a Monster.&nbsp;That’s because Red Bull promotes themselves among these groups of people. Or, imagine walking into a drugstore&nbsp;looking for toothpaste. Which one are you more likely to pick? The one you saw an advertisement of (it showed&nbsp;footage of smiling people with perfectly white teeth) or some other random paste you’ve never heard about.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Well, obviously the first one! According to Malcolm Gladwell: “Buyers make most decisions by relying on their&nbsp;two-second first impressions based on stored memories, images and feelings” (Gladwell, The Power of Thinking Without Thinking) – that means, an advertisement you saw some time ago is now embedded in your brain and will impact your choices! No matter how good the other toothpaste is, or how bad the first one might be, you will most likely choose the one you are familiar with.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Branding will not make you any money:</strong></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That’s true, it won’t. The sales of your product or service will make you money. Consistent branding across all channels increases revenue by 23%. Branding is what will make the customers choose what you offer instead of what somebody else is offering. So like, in the long run, it will make you money!<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Branding is only about product or service:</strong></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The CEO example, I wrote about above already cracks this premise. However, think of customer service – the&nbsp;experience you get when getting your problem solved by a company representative can largely impact the way&nbsp;you perceive the entire structure. True – the products or services are what drives your company forward, but&nbsp;it’s all about the aftertaste that a transaction leaves. Brand equity can be largely impacted by the quality&nbsp;of customer service.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Branding isn\'t necessary:</strong></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Many company owners believe that if they create a decent product and provide good service at the right price, the company will succeed. While those are things that every company should be doing, they will only get you so far. Consumers tend to rely on emotion rather than logic when making purchase decisions, and this is where branding your company and its products can make a difference. If your branding triggers a positive emotional response in consumers’ minds, it can mean the difference between a sale or a consumer who walks away.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Branding is expensive:</strong></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Well, it’s true that like big brands like Amazon or Pepsi spend a hell lot of money in their marketing. But branding&nbsp;your business is entirely depends on what’s the market size of your business. You don’t need to spend millions like&nbsp;Amazon or eBay. You can promote your brand with a small budget. The only thing you need to take care of that you deliver the exact thing to your customers what your brand claims. The marketing of your brand absolutely runs on emotions. So, keep your brand tone even and interactive while marketing your brand. For example, Starbucks built their brand with one single mission “Our mission: to inspire and nurture the human spirit – one person, one cup and one neighborhood at a time.” Unlike other brands, Starbucks focuses on the importance of building a community of happy and satisfied customers one step at a time. That’s made Starbucks one of the popular brands in the world.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you are low on budget then read <a href=\"http://www.efrog.com.au/blog/2019/09/10/how-to-promote-your-business-online/\">how to promote your business when you’re low on your budget.</a><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Branding is a one-shot deal:</strong></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is one of the biggest misconceptions most people have. No matter how big is your brand and how much effort you made in your branding, every business needs to review and revise their branding strategy regularly or the result will be devastating. The big example of this is “Nestle”. A few years back “<a href=\"https://www.nestle.com\">Nestle</a>” wasn’t focusing on managing their online brand management and that cost them a loss of millions. Brands like Coca-cola, Starbucks and other popular brands take care of this thing and always revise their strategy of branding.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Consumers don’t really care what the brand looks like:</strong></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is a common thought among people who are in industries that are less glamorous or those that have traditionally not focus much on looking good. However, consumers are much more intuitive than what business owners perceive these days.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>“Buyers make most decisions by relying on their two-second first impressions based on stored memories, images, and feelings.”</strong><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And most often than not, these first impressions are based on your outward appearance, which is evident right away, before they decide whether to dig deeper into your brand.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the end of the day, no matter what brand the consumer choose, they still desire products and services that they are attracted to and that they can connect with. If they feel your website looks dubious or unprofessional, chances are they might not give your brand and services a second look.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What’s more, if you are in a generic market that is lacking in any branding, what do you think would give you an edge to stand out from the crowd?<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Branding isn’t relevant to a small business like ours</strong></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Most small businesses may not think much about branding as they associate becoming a “brand” too big spendings by well-known brands. We are talking about glamorous TV or print advertising, celebrity endorsements and publicity stunts by companies such as Apple and Nike.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And it’s true that if we look at branding through this lens, it may seem overwhelming and irrelevant to small businesses. But if we dive deeper, what these activities aim for is to create “brand engagement”, which in essence is just about connecting people with the brand.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now, creating a connection with your audience is definitely relevant and essential to all businesses big or small. In fact, I’d say that branding is even more crucial for small companies as they do not have the budget to achieve branding success by pouring money into branding as the big boys do.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Therefore, small businesses have to be smart and strategic about their branding. They can do so by starting small and work on their immediate brand assets to build a strong foundation for growth. With small incremental steps, these branding efforts can one day have a domino effect and make a big difference.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Branding can be done without dedicated specialists:</strong></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Devising a successful branding strategy is far more difficult than it looks. If anyone could be doing it, there wouldn’t&nbsp;be such a thing as a dedicated marketing specialist. These kinds of services can help bring a comprehensive, creative approach to branding that implements your specific brand strategy into every design.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There you have it! Hopefully, you have enough real information on branding to start mastering your own strategy and avoid these misconceptions about branding.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Need help creating that perfect brand? <a href=\"http://www.efrog.com.au/#contactForm\">Let us help tell your brand’s unique story today!</a><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', '11 Common Misconceptions About Branding', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '73-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-01-15 13:20:11', '2020-01-15 13:20:11', '', 73, 'http://www.efrog.com.au/blog/73-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(205, 1, '2020-01-15 13:24:14', '2020-01-15 13:24:14', '5-Challenges-to-SAP-integration', '5-Challenges-to-SAP-integration', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'closed', '', '5-challenges-to-sap-integration-2', '', '', '2020-01-15 13:24:26', '2020-01-15 13:24:26', '', 79, 'http://www.efrog.com.au/blog/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/5-Challenges-to-SAP-integration.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
(206, 1, '2020-01-15 13:24:40', '2020-01-15 13:24:40', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>SAP integration is achieved by adopting some common approaches, or methodologies. Namely, integration of software applications in such a way that they use a shared database, integration using service-oriented architecture stacks (point to point direct integration and standalone enterprise service bus integration), robotic process automation and a combination of these approaches. We will learn about the challenges concerning SAP integration by discussing the merits and limitations of each of the 5 approaches below.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Shared database</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A number of software applications are integrated with an underlying shared database. All applications share and use the same data residing in that location. This ensures the data being used in different business processes is uniform as all changes to the data take instantaneous effect. The transmission of the data is relatively fast as it doesn’t have to cross lots of interfaces between the business process software application and the database.&nbsp;<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Naturally, like all technology, these advantages of the centralized repository of data shared real-time with integrated software systems, come with some trade-offs:<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Higher risk of entire SAP ERP system failure: </strong>The complete suite of software systems connected to and dependent on the database can become inoperable due to any failure of the database. All the systems connected to the database will cease functioning or function improperly if there is even a slight problem with the database.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>The criticality of database changes and operations:</strong> Any tweaking to the database will entail a thorough check of all the integrated applications to see if the changes are compliant to the smooth functioning of each of the applications.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Risks to data security:</strong> Since several SAP or third-party applications have access to the database, security may be compromised on account of widespread access.&nbsp;</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Compatibility with different products: </strong>Software systems operating on databases like the CRM application of Salesforce and the SAP ERP suite cannot be integrated with each other due to the existence of separate internal databases.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Service-oriented architecture stacks</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Service-oriented architecture stacks or SOA stacks, being an integration of several independent apps and services comprise of multiple products. These products are application servers, management and development tools, orchestration engines, etc. The SOA integration architecture is quite robust due to the fact that it’s integrated apps are coupled loosely and free to mature organically. The <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Service-oriented_architecture\">SOA architecture</a> helps to bring costs down as it is easier to tend to stacked apps compared to maintaining each and every constituent application as a standalone. The reliability-factor of stacked apps is also higher than that of separate standalone programs. Once a stacked framework has been implemented, adding additional applications for supporting new business processes is not too expensive. SOA stacking allows businesses to create, consolidate and deploy services and add/modify them as required. It also allows the convenience of the rapid introduction of new services, easy modification of existing ones and compatibility to external systems.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Disadvantages of the SOA approach:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>The disadvantage of the SOA approach is that multiple products in the stack have to be configured and deployed. Since a stack usually has a large number of products within its framework, this can take time.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>SOA implementation takes a long time, at times years. This extends the initial implementation phase over a considerable period of time and hence drives up the initial implementation cost.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Also, developers working to build the stack framework have to have expertise in each of the proprietary software slated to be included in the stack. So recruitment of new developers will have to be given careful attention as it is mandatory that they have the specialist knowledge that went into creation, deployment, and maintenance of the stack so far.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>At the same time, significant initial investments, complicated configurations, and change management, demanding network and system monitoring make up the dark side of SOA solutions.&nbsp;</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>SOA-based integration is of two types: point-to-point integration and enterprise service bus (ESB).&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Point-to-point integration with SAP interfaces </strong>is complex, expensive and tedious. It isn\'t flexible as it forms rigid links; and is suited for the SAP environment only. Also, It is less suitable to a SAP environment that is constantly evolving. Business processes of an organization are bound to change constantly due to improvements and adjustments. The point-to-point integration architecture lacks additional touchpoints between the integrated systems and the resulting dependencies are unreliable. This isn’t an ideal long term investment.&nbsp;<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This type of integration is beneficial when there are few services or systems to be integrated. It’s when the size and complexity of the business ERP increase that the point-to-point approach tends to become counter-intuitive as explained above.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Enterprise service bus (ESB) </strong>is a fundamental component of the SOA stack. It primarily acts as a messenger between applications and components. It is able to maintain and manage traditional SOA stacks efficiently. ESBs come with their own management tools. They also integrate well with the management tools currently being used in the organization. They do not come laden with a heap of new technologies that have to be learned to work with them. They integrate well with the development tools and technologies already in use. Integration using ESB reduces upfront costs.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The disadvantage of the ESB approach is that like a shared database, there is a high dependency of every integrated software application on it. Any problems with the ESB will freeze up the entire ERP system.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Robotic process automation (RPA)</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>AI robots do not need to be programmed but can mimic and learn repetitive user operations on the system frontend GUI. This ability of a robot is not limited to just one application but they can interact with several applications. Implementing RPA doesn’t require major changes to the system or programming. There is no need for APIs as this integration is at a user interface level. It is quick.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Disadvantages:<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>There are limits to AI intuitiveness. They can’t be applied to an environment where the trigger isn’t clear.&nbsp;</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Any changes to the GUI will require a change in associated robotics as well.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Mixed approach</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is what is usually found in most integrations. It has been found in the real world that any one approach is not sufficient to address all the functional needs of a business ERP system.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But even a custom approach is not without certain limitations. They are discussed below:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Data quality</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Compensation events need to be designed to mitigate transaction failure or to adjust against the adverse business impact of time-consuming ones.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Extra effort has to be put in to create the flexibility of data structures.&nbsp;</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Backup and Archival necessity</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A contingency plan for backup, backup monitoring, and disaster recovery is vital. This becomes especially complex as cloud services and cloud integration has phased out conventional physical infrastructure. They have their own separate legal regulations that have to be looked into.&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Quality Control</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The field and scope of failures and errors in SAP environment and activity is vast. To add to that, a shared test environment isn’t easy to achieve due to the involvement of numerous legacy and SAP systems. Working with multiple languages and protocols is not easy. The challenges in monitoring evolving connections with SAP sub-systems, coupling and decoupling services, time-triggers, particular events that drive certain processes, asynchronous communication in connectors, etc is considerable.&nbsp;<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A significant amount of effort, time and resources are expended by businesses to meet these challenges. Also, this isn\'t something that can be limited to a small or focus group; numerous stakeholders, decision-makers and vendors have to participate.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1>Conclusion</h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A well-designed, rigorously checked and diligently monitored SAP integration helps a business reap insights and gain efficiencies. These are must-haves in these times to conquer higher and more complex ground.&nbsp;<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>eFrog’s secure and reliable <a href=\"http://www.efrog.com.au/\">software development solutions</a> help run business processes and conveniently exchange data between onsite infrastructure, cloud platforms, and external third-party applications. The integrations and connectors eFrog provides are easy to learn and assimilate, ensuring that clients don\'t have to waste effort, time or resources on training and staffing around these technologies. The integration designs are created to minimize developmental costs to the client.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', '5 Challenges to SAP Integration You Should Know', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '79-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-01-15 13:24:40', '2020-01-15 13:24:40', '', 79, 'http://www.efrog.com.au/blog/79-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
